caption: Don’t recommend for takeout or delivery, food used to be good, particularly for dining in, but this recent delivery order’s easily the worst I’ve had since pandemic started (order takeout from restaurants about once a week to support businesses).  Ordered 5 items, out of them 3 were not fresh, including a $11 salad with portion only filled a soup bowl and decomposed leafy greens mixed in between with unpleasant smells, basically inedible so had to throw it away. Then the chicken skewers had raw meaty taste. Lastly raw octopus in wasabi, smelled ok but not fresh in the taste, since it’s raw, didn’t want to risk it, so paid about $40 for the entire order, couldn’t eat more than half of it due to quality, so $40 ended up equivalent to a rice ball and 3 takoyaki.

I love the old Ittoku, I used to go there for dinner at least once a week. But this new one is so bad and disappointed. The food and drinks are about 30% more expensive than the old place, which is totally fine if the food quality can be maintained . But sadly, the food is way worse than the old place. Some dishes are way too salty, some dishes are flavorless, and the worst thing is, the sashimi is not as fresh as before. I do not think I will come back again, and I really really miss the old Ittoku, which is the BEST Japanese restaurant in Boston.

I'm just being overly critical since this used to be my favorite izakaya in the entire USA but now it's just average... and to lose my favorite place leaves a void I need to fill. Sigh.

I've stopped in twice here for dinner with my girlfriend. We are both a little particular about our sushi and both times we were incredibly impressed at how good the sushi was. When the restaurant is full of Asian people its usually a good sign. They have some of the freshest fish. Usually shrimp is the "meh" sushi option but this time it was the star of the show. The roe was salty and popped in your mouth as you bit down. The small plates came out quickly and we were comfortable ordering in rounds that fit our speed. They have a good selection of sake that goes great with the sushi. By the way, they also have some other Japanese izakaya favorites like grilled skewers, soups, salads, and other hot entrees. Really good. Really authentic.

Best, most authentic Japanese food in Boston. Portions can be small, but extremely always tasty. They’re perfect for sharing! Try their okonomiyaki (cabbage pancake), their wide assortment of yakitori (chicken skewers), or their yakisoba (fried noodles). For dessert, try their flan! It’s so good.  Most things on their menu will satisfy even Japanese locals, with a few exceptions. Don’t come here for ramen. They don’t specialize in it and thus will not provide the experience you’ll get at other places like Sapporo Ramen or Santouka.  Their sake assortment is also great, and they have many non-alcoholic drinks for those underage, including my favorite Japanese drink: Calpico soda. Service is great, and the place is always full, no matter when I go. I think they’re planning to move to Porter Square so I’m not sure what their restaurant will look like there.

The very best Japanese restaurant I have ever been in.  We shared several plates including delicious fried smelts with an amazing dipping sauce, goyza with meltingly tender dough surrounding a delicious, fragrant sausage filling.  We also shared brazed tongue; something others may not consider trying, but it was tender and had a subtle beefy taste.  It almost melted in our mouths.  One of our table had a skewer of three quail's eggs wrapped in bacon, another had skewers of beef and another had silken tofu, not cooked, in a light soy-based sauce .  All declared their food superlative.  The only mistake I made was to not order a beer to go with the meal.  I had a glass of Sauvingnon Blanc which was too acidic for the food we chose.  My fault, not the restaurant's.  I can see I will be back there every time I go to Boston.

The range of dishes served at Ittoku is fantastic, and as another reviewer mentioned, the menu style is closer to what you'd find at a restaurant in Japan, with Japanese text and graphics. There are also plenty of dishes I would not have expected to be served outside of Japan. Staff were friendly and the atmosphere was lively but not rowdy.  Almost everything we ordered was better than expected. The squid salad had a lot of squid and delicious dressing, the takoyaki had a good texture on the outside with that hot gooey goodness on the inside. Note that you do not get bonito with the takoyaki. We asked if they had forgotten it, but the waitress told us that they simply served it that way. We asked for some on the side and they obliged.  The okonomiyaki, however, was a huge disappointment. We were bummed because that was the primary reason we came. It definitely did not have the crispness on the bottom that is characteristic of the dish. I remember the menu made mention of it being on a hot plate, but it came out on a normal plate and so had a very soft texture all the way through.  I will definitely go back for a meal, but will definitely not be re-ordering the okonomiyaki. Everything else, though, I look forward to trying!
